{"term":"2012","caseName":"United States v. Kebodeaux","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/2012/12-418","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - April 17, 2013","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/roberts6/oral_argument_audio/22077","transcript":[{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"We'll hear argument first this morning in Case 12-418, United States v. Kebodeaux.","start":0,"stop":7.154,"duration":7.15},{"text":"Mr. Dreeben.","start":7.154,"stop":8.12,"duration":0.97}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court:","start":8.12,"stop":11.289,"duration":3.17},{"text":"Convicted sex offenders pose a serious threat to public safety.","start":11.289,"stop":15.693,"duration":4.4},{"text":"When those convictions are entered under Federal law, Congress has the authority to impose both a criminal and a civil sanction for that conduct in order to protect the public.","start":15.693,"stop":28.233,"duration":12.54},{"text":"The Fifth Circuit in this case applied a per se rule that once Respondent had completed his military sentence, Congress lost authority to apply a civil sanction for that violation of Federal law.","start":28.233,"stop":43.243,"duration":15.01},{"text":"That per se rule is wrong.","start":43.243,"stop":46.129,"duration":2.89},{"text":"Nothing in Article I prevents Congress from legislating retroactively with respect to civil remedies for past violations of Federal law.","start":46.129,"stop":57.337,"duration":11.21},{"text":"The Ex Post Facto Clause, the Due Process Clause, and Article I analysis under the Necessary and Proper Clause all provide some degree of protection against retroactive provisions, but no per se rule bars Congress from applying sex offender registration requirements, which this Court has held to be civil remedies not barred by the Ex Post Facto Clause to past Federal criminal convictions.","start":57.337,"stop":88.039,"duration":30.7},{"text":"Now--","start":88.039,"stop":88.808,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"What's the limit of that power?","start":88.808,"stop":90.408,"duration":1.6},{"text":"How -- for any Federal conviction, whether it's related to sex offense or anything else, Congress could impose any kind of registration requirement?","start":90.408,"stop":103.4,"duration":12.99}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, certainly, Justice Sotomayor--","start":103.4,"stop":105.667,"duration":2.27}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Could it ask every convicted Federal felon to come in for a DNA test, because we know that people who have been convicted of a crime are more likely to be recidivists?","start":105.667,"stop":117.791,"duration":12.12}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, Justice Sotomayor, there are independent constitutional limits both outside of Article I and within Article I that mean that I will answer your question no, it's not the case that my position today means there are no limits.","start":117.791,"stop":133.17,"duration":15.38},{"text":"There are limits.","start":133.17,"stop":134.27,"duration":1.1},{"text":"If we--","start":134.27,"stop":134.97,"duration":0.7}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"So what -- what is the limit?","start":134.97,"stop":136.455,"duration":1.49},{"text":"Is it just safety?","start":136.455,"stop":138.205,"duration":1.75},{"text":"It can't be just safety of the public, because you just said that it doesn't apply to recidivist Federal offenders, generally.","start":138.205,"stop":147.596,"duration":9.39}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"--The -- the principal limitation on retroactive legislation is the Ex Post Facto Clause.","start":147.596,"stop":153.131,"duration":5.53},{"text":"Indeed, there would have been no need for an Ex Post Facto Clause if the Fifth Circuit were correct.","start":153.131,"stop":158.702,"duration":5.57}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't understand.","start":158.702,"stop":159.285,"duration":0.58},{"text":"I just posited a civil registration for Federal offenders of any kind.","start":159.285,"stop":165.474,"duration":6.19},{"text":"That's not ex post facto under your theory, so--","start":165.474,"stop":168.26,"duration":2.79}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"So if -- if the Court agrees that it's not a punitive measure and it is a remedial measure--","start":168.26,"stop":172.878,"duration":4.62}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, I don't know if I agree with that, but accept -- accepting that hypothetical.","start":172.878,"stop":176.08,"duration":3.2}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, if you don't agree with it, then you'll be going on the Ex Post Facto Clause, and you won't be getting to Article I.","start":176.08,"stop":181.401,"duration":5.32}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"No, you know, that's settled law.","start":181.401,"stop":182.601,"duration":1.2},{"text":"Whether it's right or wrong is a different issue.","start":182.601,"stop":184.936,"duration":2.34}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"It is settled law, and that means that sex offender registration provisions aren't punitive.","start":184.936,"stop":191.173,"duration":6.24},{"text":"The question here is, are they within Article I.","start":191.173,"stop":193.391,"duration":2.22},{"text":"And the Court in United States v. Comstock went through an elaborate Necessary and Proper Clause analysis--","start":193.391,"stop":201.397,"duration":8.01}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, in Comstock, it was very different than the situation here, because the analysis was that the Federal Government basically was the source of the problem in incarcerating sex offenders away from the State so that no State felt an obligation to do something with the problem of their release.","start":201.397,"stop":217.924,"duration":16.53},{"text":"You don't have anything of that sort here.","start":217.924,"stop":219.526,"duration":1.6}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"--No.","start":219.526,"stop":220.359,"duration":0.83},{"text":"This provision, Mr. Chief Justice, rests on a different analysis than Comstock.","start":220.359,"stop":225.846,"duration":5.49},{"text":"In Comstock, the problem was caused by Federal custody that, as Your Honor has said, broke the relationship between the individual and some State that might take cognizance of him for purposes of sex offender civil commitment.","start":225.846,"stop":241.689,"duration":15.84},{"text":"The basis for the statute in Comstock was that people in Federal custody, regardless of the nature of their prior convictions, might pose threats if released.","start":241.689,"stop":253.014,"duration":11.33},{"text":"The basis for the statute in this case is not that the individual was in Federal custody.","start":253.014,"stop":258.668,"duration":5.65},{"text":"Federal custody is irrelevant to it.","start":258.668,"stop":260.536,"duration":1.87},{"text":"The basis for the statute in this case is that this is a sex offender in violation of Federal law, and Congress has the authority to impose, as was done in this case, criminal punishment, but it also has the authority to impose civil regulatory sanctions.","start":260.536,"stop":277.997,"duration":17.46}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"So I assume that applies to all Federal crimes, right?","start":277.997,"stop":281.683,"duration":3.69},{"text":"Anyone convicted of any Federal crime can thereafter be subjected to whatever civil restraints Congress later decides are -- are a good idea in order to prevent that crime, that type of crime from reoccurring, right?","start":281.683,"stop":302.347,"duration":20.66},{"text":"I mean, nothing peculiar here about sex crimes.","start":302.347,"stop":305.981,"duration":3.63},{"text":"Any -- any crime Congress can later decide, you know, it would be a good idea if when -- when a person has committed, I don't know, crime with the use of a gun, we -- we impose retroactively all sorts of different civil limitations.","start":305.981,"stop":321.926,"duration":15.94}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Justice Scalia, there is no per se rule in Article I that forbids retroactive civil regulations imposed on a Federal offender.","start":321.926,"stop":333.199,"duration":11.27},{"text":"So the question--","start":333.199,"stop":334.484,"duration":1.28}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"No, no, that's not the point, that it's -- that it's retroactive.","start":334.484,"stop":339.555,"duration":5.07},{"text":"The point is that it is not in execution of a Federal power.","start":339.555,"stop":344.674,"duration":5.12}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, I think the whole point in this case is that it's retroactive, because there isn't any serious dispute that if somebody commits a Federal sex offense they can be placed on supervised release for life so--","start":344.674,"stop":356.314,"duration":11.64}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"That would be an execution of a Federal power--","start":356.314,"stop":358.699,"duration":2.38}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, so is this.","start":358.699,"stop":359.883,"duration":1.18}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"--the power -- the power to prevent that crime and to punish it.","start":359.883,"stop":362.151,"duration":2.27}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, but Congress's power is not limited to preventing and punishing crimes through criminal law.","start":362.151,"stop":369.657,"duration":7.51},{"text":"Except for a brief interlude under United States v. Halper where this Court viewed double jeopardy as precluding multiple criminal and civil sanctions, the Court has recognized that when someone violates Federal law they're exposed both to criminal punishment and to civil sanctions.","start":369.657,"stop":387.452,"duration":17.8},{"text":"The criminal punishment has to comply with the Ex Post Facto Clause; the civil sanctions do not.","start":387.452,"stop":394.106,"duration":6.65},{"text":"So what the--","start":394.106,"stop":395.089,"duration":0.98}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"But they have to be imposed simultaneously as -- as the punishment for the crime of which the individual has been convicted.","start":395.089,"stop":403.478,"duration":8.39},{"text":"Here, the trial is over, the conviction is over, and then some years later the Federal Government decides, oh, it would be a good idea if people who have committed sex crimes are -- are subjected to these limitations.","start":403.478,"stop":414.52,"duration":11.04},{"text":"That's quite different from imposing that simultaneously as -- as a punishment for the crime.","start":414.52,"stop":420.424,"duration":5.9},{"text":"This is not a punishment for the crime, right?","start":420.424,"stop":422.542,"duration":2.12}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"--That's precisely--","start":422.542,"stop":424.076,"duration":1.53}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":424.076,"stop":424.576,"duration":0.5}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"--what makes it a civil sanction.","start":424.576,"stop":425.928,"duration":1.35},{"text":"But, Justice Scalia, Your Honor is presupposing that Congress can only react to a sex crime through the criminal law and that it must have those laws in place at the time of the punishment, and there is no such Article I precept.","start":425.928,"stop":442.353,"duration":16.43}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"So your argument depends in no way on the fact that he was convicted of a Federal offense or -- or incarcerated for that offense, nothing at all?","start":442.353,"stop":451.276,"duration":8.92},{"text":"We're just here arguing about the retroactivity under -- whether they have the authority under Article I to impose punishment for not registering under State law?","start":451.276,"stop":461.167,"duration":9.89}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"This case turns entirely on the fact that the defendant is a Federal offender.","start":461.167,"stop":466.303,"duration":5.14},{"text":"The source of power in question was the power to regulate the armed forces.","start":466.303,"stop":471.772,"duration":5.47},{"text":"This is an individual who committed a sex crime while in the armed forces.","start":471.772,"stop":475.426,"duration":3.65},{"text":"And Congress's power to address that and to prescribe remedies for it both civil and criminal is entirely tied to the Federal nature of the offense.","start":475.426,"stop":485.032,"duration":9.61}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we start out with the power under the Constitution to make rules to regulate the military and we end up with a registration requirement that applies to someone who's not in the military and perhaps is not even living anywhere near any military installation.","start":485.032,"stop":504.594,"duration":19.56},{"text":"So what would be helpful for me is to start out with the constitutional provision, identify a purpose of that that is served by this civil registration that is imposed later, and trace this whole progress through the Necessary and Proper Clause.","start":504.594,"stop":522.824,"duration":18.23}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"Justice Alito, I think the most helpful way to do that would be for me to progress through a series of examples that illustrate how protecting the public against a Federal sex offender is a legitimate aim under the Necessary and Proper Clause to implement the underlying constitutional authority.","start":522.824,"stop":540.536,"duration":17.71}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":540.536,"stop":541.036,"duration":0.5}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"So start with a sex offender who commits a sex offense in the military, is tried, court-martialed and sentenced.","start":541.036,"stop":548.023,"duration":6.99},{"text":"Subject to cruel and unusual punishment limitations, due process limitations, et cetera, that individual can be incarcerated, placed on supervised release potentially up to life.","start":548.023,"stop":561.199,"duration":13.18},{"text":"A condition of supervised release, well-recognized and now mandated by Federal law, is that that individual register as a sex offender.","start":561.199,"stop":570.555,"duration":9.36},{"text":"And the reason that that is tied to Federal law is that when an individual violates Federal law it is a legitimate purpose of Congress to protect the public against recidivism by that individual.","start":570.555,"stop":583.713,"duration":13.16},{"text":"So that's the criminal example that I believe is undisputed.","start":583.713,"stop":587.332,"duration":3.62},{"text":"Now, suppose that the Federal Government didn't actually get the sex offender while he was in the military.","start":587.332,"stop":594.087,"duration":6.75},{"text":"It missed the crime, but later information comes to light still within the statute of limitations that shows that while this person was in the military they committed a sex offense.","start":594.087,"stop":603.776,"duration":9.69},{"text":"This court in United States ex rel. Toth v. Quarles made clear that that individual can be tried in an Article III court for his criminal violation even though he's out of the military.","start":603.776,"stop":616.684,"duration":12.91},{"text":"It's enforcing the rules that were impressed upon him at the time while he was in the military.","start":616.684,"stop":622.94,"duration":6.26},{"text":"Now let me give a civil example and then I will bring it right back to this case.","start":622.94,"stop":628.059,"duration":5.12},{"text":"Suppose that Congress concludes that sex offenses in the military are a very serious problem and that there are a lot of people who have escaped prosecution because of lax interest in pursuing those crimes.","start":628.059,"stop":640.299,"duration":12.24},{"text":"And after a period of years, it sets up a board of inquiry and it says this board of inquiry is going to look into sex offenses that were committed at the time that people were in the military, even if they're out of the military, and we're going to subpoena people to testify, and if individuals are determined in a civil proceeding to have committed sex offenses they may have their military records revised, they may lose military benefits, and they may have other civil sanctions imposed upon them.","start":640.299,"stop":668.236,"duration":27.94}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"When you say in a civil proceeding, you mean?","start":668.236,"stop":670.502,"duration":2.27}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, noncriminal.","start":670.502,"stop":671.771,"duration":1.27},{"text":"Noncriminal.","start":671.771,"stop":672.971,"duration":1.2}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"So it's just by a preponderance of the evidence we think this guy probably, you know, 51/49, committed a sex crime.","start":672.971,"stop":679.175,"duration":6.2}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"Not going to be a criminal punishment that's imposed at the end of the day.","start":679.175,"stop":682.894,"duration":3.72}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"So just -- just more -- more likely than not is the test.","start":682.894,"stop":687.298,"duration":4.4}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"That's an acceptable level of proof for the civil law.","start":687.298,"stop":690.9,"duration":3.6},{"text":"And if Congress can do that in order to protect the integrity of the military and to promote confidence in the military, then it's a very small step, if any step at all, to SORNA.","start":690.9,"stop":703.909,"duration":13.01}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, but if they can do that.","start":703.909,"stop":705.375,"duration":1.47},{"text":"But that's not what they've done here.","start":705.375,"stop":706.944,"duration":1.57},{"text":"Your argument, as you told me a while ago, is linked to the Federal offense and the incarceration.","start":706.944,"stop":714.431,"duration":7.49}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, absolute -- well, Mr. Chief Justice, it's not linked to the incarceration.","start":714.431,"stop":717.983,"duration":3.55},{"text":"This is the difference between this case and Comstock, and this is why the Solicitor General's concession in Comstock on which the Fifth Circuit heavily relied has no applicability here.","start":717.983,"stop":728.941,"duration":10.96},{"text":"In Comstock, it was irrelevant what offense the individual had been committed.","start":728.941,"stop":733.594,"duration":4.65},{"text":"The problem was he was in Federal custody, he was sexually dangerous at the time he would be released.","start":733.594,"stop":740.682,"duration":7.09},{"text":"Ties had been broken between him and the community, and if he were released it would pose a threat to public safety that the Federal Government had power to protect against.","start":740.682,"stop":750.604,"duration":9.92}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Because the States were not doing anything about it.","start":750.604,"stop":753.556,"duration":2.95}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":753.556,"stop":754.175,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Here you have a situation where I think at the time every State dealt with the issue of whether the sex offenders should have to register or not.","start":754.175,"stop":761.496,"duration":7.32}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":761.496,"stop":762.662,"duration":1.17},{"text":"But Federal law did as well and Federal law provided encouragement.","start":762.662,"stop":766.733,"duration":4.07},{"text":"This is actually a primary example of partnership between State governments and the Federal Government.","start":766.733,"stop":773.719,"duration":6.99},{"text":"The Federal Government offers financial support, it offers logistical assistance, it offers tremendous resources of the U.S. marshals to track down sex offenders.","start":773.719,"stop":784.444,"duration":10.72},{"text":"And as this Court said in Carr v. United States, it was entirely reasonable for Congress to have assigned a special responsibility for prosecuting Federal sex offenders who failed to register.","start":784.444,"stop":798.371,"duration":13.93},{"text":"This was integral to this Court's reasoning in Carr, where the Court was confronted with two provisions of 2250, the criminal sex offense provision under SORNA.","start":798.371,"stop":808.727,"duration":10.36},{"text":"For State offenders, there had to be travel in interstate commerce; for Federal offenders there didn't.","start":808.727,"stop":815.146,"duration":6.42},{"text":"The Government argued that the provisions ought to be given as co-extensive a reach as possible so that the coverage of the statute would be equally comprehensive for both State and Federal.","start":815.146,"stop":825.771,"duration":10.63},{"text":"And this Court--","start":825.771,"stop":826.321,"duration":0.55}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"The discussion so far has assumed, your discussion primarily, that there's this line between civil and criminal, we don't need to worry about ex post facto.","start":826.321,"stop":836.996,"duration":10.67},{"text":"Is that line made clear in our precedents or is there some room to argue that if the line is somewhat blurred that there may be ex post facto concerns here and that that in turn is a reason for constitutional avoidance when we evaluate your argument?","start":836.996,"stop":855.29,"duration":18.29},{"text":"Is that -- is the civil -- a criminal distinction with reference to ex post facto clause absolutely foreclosed and clear in the facts of this case?","start":855.29,"stop":865.146,"duration":9.86}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"--Yes, it is, I believe, Justice Kennedy.","start":865.146,"stop":867.515,"duration":2.37},{"text":"In an opinion that you wrote for the Court, Smith v. Doe, which considered the retroactivity of Alaska's sex offender registration and notification provisions, which are similar but not identical, to the Federal provisions, the Court went through the established analysis to determine whether the legislature had intended a punitive effect and if it didn't, whether there was the clearest proof that it was punishment in purpose and effect.","start":867.515,"stop":894.832,"duration":27.32},{"text":"Notwithstanding the legislature's intent, the Court upheld the retroactive applicability of sex offender registration and notification, making clear that it is not governed by the Ex Post Facto Clause.","start":894.832,"stop":907.508,"duration":12.68},{"text":"Now, that's not to say that an individual couldn't argue that SORNA is different or an individual couldn't argue that the Due Process Clause makes it either irrational or substantively off limits to impose this kind of civil remedy.","start":907.508,"stop":923.185,"duration":15.68},{"text":"The individual can also argue that running this through the Comstock factors, it's not reasonably adapted to fulfilling Congress's aim.","start":923.185,"stop":933.291,"duration":10.11},{"text":"But what the Fifth Circuit did is apply a per se rule that it drew, I think, from the Solicitor General's statement in Comstock that once an individual got out of custody and was back in the control of the State and within its jurisdiction and population, then the Federal Government couldn't reach out and commit him as a sex offender.","start":933.291,"stop":953.753,"duration":20.46},{"text":"And there are two main distinctions between that concession and this case.","start":953.753,"stop":957.989,"duration":4.24},{"text":"The first is, as I've already alluded to, the Government's argument in Comstock was based on custody.","start":957.989,"stop":964.243,"duration":6.25},{"text":"This case is based on the consequences of the conviction itself.","start":964.243,"stop":968.88,"duration":4.64},{"text":"The second distinction is that committing somebody civilly is a massive intrusion on that individual's relationship with the State.","start":968.88,"stop":977.82,"duration":8.94},{"text":"The individual has been brought within Federal custody; they have no relationship with the State anymore.","start":977.82,"stop":983.64,"duration":5.82},{"text":"Whereas sex offender notification is far more accommodating of State interests.","start":983.64,"stop":988.859,"duration":5.22}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Dreeben--","start":988.859,"stop":989.544,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"To -- to what does this civil -- civil-criminal line apply?","start":989.544,"stop":992.913,"duration":3.37},{"text":"Suppose instead of a registration requirement, Congress just decided, you know, our past punishments for sex offenses have not been -- have not been severe enough, and so we are now going to impose a civil fine on all -- all persons who have been convicted in Federal court of sex crimes.","start":992.913,"stop":1018.611,"duration":25.7},{"text":"It's a civil -- it's a civil penalty, not a criminal penalty.","start":1018.611,"stop":1022.265,"duration":3.65},{"text":"That's okay?","start":1022.265,"stop":1022.915,"duration":0.65}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"It's not per se barred by Article I, Justice Scalia.","start":1022.915,"stop":1027.384,"duration":4.47},{"text":"The question of whether it's constitutional is really a question of individual rights analysis and whether it passes through the necessary and proper gate under the considerations similar to what the Court looked at in Comstock.","start":1027.384,"stop":1040.893,"duration":13.51}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"I find that difficult to believe that--","start":1040.893,"stop":1042.762,"duration":1.87}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, there's no--","start":1042.762,"stop":1044.028,"duration":1.27}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"--that whether it's ex post facto and impermissible or not is simply eliminated, that issue was eliminated by simply calling it civil.","start":1044.028,"stop":1055.67,"duration":11.64}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, it's not eliminated.","start":1055.67,"stop":1056.553,"duration":0.88},{"text":"It still is available for an individual to argue, as Respondent did in this case in the district court but abandoned long before he got to the court of appeals, that it violates due process, that it violates ex post facto.","start":1056.553,"stop":1069.33,"duration":12.78}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm talking about the -- ex post facto.","start":1069.33,"stop":1071.563,"duration":2.23}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"He can argue that.","start":1071.563,"stop":1073.032,"duration":1.47},{"text":"I submit that he will lose.","start":1073.032,"stop":1075.483,"duration":2.45}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Because it's civil.","start":1075.483,"stop":1076.566,"duration":1.08}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"If it in fact is civil and passes through this Court's analysis, then yes.","start":1076.566,"stop":1082.553,"duration":5.99}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I find that difficult to grasp.","start":1082.553,"stop":1085.689,"duration":3.14}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it's actually quite well established as a principle of double jeopardy law in cases like Hudson v. United States and United States v. Ursery.","start":1085.689,"stop":1094.445,"duration":8.76},{"text":"It's established in ex post facto law as a consequence of Smith v. Doe.","start":1094.445,"stop":1098.682,"duration":4.24},{"text":"It's the foundation for deciding whether a proceeding requires preponderance of the evidence versus proof beyond a reasonable of doubt.","start":1098.682,"stop":1105.336,"duration":6.65},{"text":"The Court has articulated this line in a variety of contexts.","start":1105.336,"stop":1108.705,"duration":3.37}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Your argument based -- your argument based on Congress's authority with respect to the military, your Article I argument, and you say it doesn't make a difference that he's no longer in the military, does that -- do you come out differently if the basis for jurisdiction is asserted to be inter -- interstate commerce?","start":1108.705,"stop":1127.499,"duration":18.79}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":1127.499,"stop":1128.284,"duration":0.79},{"text":"As long--","start":1128.284,"stop":1129.384,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The fact that somebody at some time in their life traveled across State lines means that the Federal Government can go back, even though their activity that's challenged in the particular instance is only intrastate, and still assert jurisdiction over them?","start":1129.384,"stop":1144.544,"duration":15.16}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, that would probably fail a Necessary and Proper Clause analysis, in which there has to be a showing that the measure is plainly adapted to furthering the underlying power.","start":1144.544,"stop":1155.519,"duration":10.97},{"text":"This is not a difficult problem that the Court has never confronted before.","start":1155.519,"stop":1159.803,"duration":4.28},{"text":"It has resulted in difficult permutations on particular facts, but the Court has always recognized that there is broad Necessary and Proper Clause authority subject to limits.","start":1159.803,"stop":1170.195,"duration":10.39},{"text":"Those limits--","start":1170.195,"stop":1170.778,"duration":0.58}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"--As broad as that authority is, perhaps I'm going back to Justice Alito's question, which is if you put aside that it's part of the punishment because you say it's not part of the punishment, you want us not to look at it as punishment because otherwise you'd run into the ex post facto problem, you're saying we have a need today.","start":1170.778,"stop":1191.859,"duration":21.08},{"text":"Outside of protecting the public from a recidivist, what's the interest?","start":1191.859,"stop":1200.047,"duration":8.19},{"text":"Because that wasn't enough in Comstock.","start":1200.047,"stop":1204.499,"duration":4.45},{"text":"We made it very clear that wasn't enough.","start":1204.499,"stop":1206.868,"duration":2.37},{"text":"So if you take out all of the punishment aspects of this, which you should have done at the time he was sentenced and not now, what remains in terms of the Federal interest?","start":1206.868,"stop":1217.676,"duration":10.81}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"--Justice Sotomayor--","start":1217.676,"stop":1218.876,"duration":1.2}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"What's promoted?","start":1218.876,"stop":1220.211,"duration":1.34}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"--There is a sufficient Federal interest in protecting the public from someone who committed a Federal crime.","start":1220.211,"stop":1227.032,"duration":6.82},{"text":"Supervised release essentially performs that function.","start":1227.032,"stop":1230.984,"duration":3.95}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"But that was -- why did we even bother going through anything in Comstock?","start":1230.984,"stop":1234.388,"duration":3.4},{"text":"If that stands alone as a Federal interest, then anything we do at any point with respect to any person who's violated a Federal law would stand in the same shoes.","start":1234.388,"stop":1246.861,"duration":12.47}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"It's a valid--","start":1246.861,"stop":1248.245,"duration":1.38}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"You could do whatever civil penalties you want for as long as you want.","start":1248.245,"stop":1251.897,"duration":3.65},{"text":"We go back to my initial question and Justice--","start":1251.897,"stop":1254.399,"duration":2.5}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"--Justice Sotomayor, really, the answer to your question is the same.","start":1254.399,"stop":1257.817,"duration":3.42},{"text":"The answer to all of your questions is the same, which is that there is an analysis that the Court went through in Comstock where it took into consideration history, it took into consideration the nature of the fit between the purpose of Congress and the activity that it was regulated.","start":1257.817,"stop":1275.013,"duration":17.2},{"text":"It took into account the degree to which the State interests were accommodated, and it took into account the degree of attenuation between the regulation and the underlying offense.","start":1275.013,"stop":1286.07,"duration":11.06},{"text":"And it -- it didn't open up Congress to say any offense you've ever committed means Congress owns you for life, it can do whatever you want.","start":1286.07,"stop":1294.342,"duration":8.27},{"text":"It has to pass through an analysis.","start":1294.342,"stop":1296.326,"duration":1.98},{"text":"But the Fifth Circuit never conducted that analysis except for believing that once the individual had completed military service, once the individual had completed his criminal sentence, Congress lost all authority.","start":1296.326,"stop":1309.936,"duration":13.61}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm getting confused between two different assertions of a Federal interest.","start":1309.936,"stop":1315.173,"duration":5.24},{"text":"Earlier you talked about the integrity of the military forces.","start":1315.173,"stop":1320.493,"duration":5.32},{"text":"They go back later, they think they should address the fact that people were engaging in criminal activities when in the military, they weren't -- they weren't found out, they weren't prosecuted.","start":1320.493,"stop":1333.051,"duration":12.56},{"text":"Later on they can go back.","start":1333.051,"stop":1334.267,"duration":1.22},{"text":"But then you say that the interest that's at issue here is preventing recidivism, and that doesn't seem to have anything to do with the integrity of the military force.","start":1334.267,"stop":1343.775,"duration":9.51}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it does because when the criminal law finds someone who has violated Federal law, many of the purposes of the sanctions that are imposed on that individual are public protection purposes and anti-recidivism purposes.","start":1343.775,"stop":1360.035,"duration":16.26},{"text":"Most of the things that are done on supervised release fulfill those purposes.","start":1360.035,"stop":1365.188,"duration":5.15},{"text":"If those purposes were not validly connected to taking someone who's violated criminal law and imposing a suite of sanctions on them, then supervised release would apparently be beyond Congress's authority.","start":1365.188,"stop":1379.365,"duration":14.18}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"It -- it seems to me that when -- when you say that as your answer to the Chief Justice, you're -- you're no longer relying on -- on the power to regulate the military.","start":1379.365,"stop":1390.923,"duration":11.56},{"text":"You're relying on -- on some general Federal power to protect citizens against people who have committed any Federal crimes.","start":1390.923,"stop":1401.445,"duration":10.52},{"text":"And I -- I don't see that enumerated power in the Constitution.","start":1401.445,"stop":1405.497,"duration":4.05},{"text":"Yes, I see a power to regulate the military, but your description, it has nothing to do with regulating the military.","start":1405.497,"stop":1412.003,"duration":6.51},{"text":"It has to do with protecting the -- the public at large from people who have committed Federal crimes, military or not.","start":1412.003,"stop":1419.907,"duration":7.9}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"As the Court has pointed out numerous times, including in Comstock, there is very little authority in the Constitution in an enumerated way for criminal law at all.","start":1419.907,"stop":1429.881,"duration":9.97},{"text":"All of criminal law, with the exception of a handful of instances that are specified in the Constitution, comes in by virtue of the Necessary and Proper Clause.","start":1429.881,"stop":1438.921,"duration":9.04}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right, because it protects Federal functions.","start":1438.921,"stop":1441.272,"duration":2.35},{"text":"The Federal -- the criminal applicability to the armed forces protects the function of regulating the armed forces.","start":1441.272,"stop":1447.509,"duration":6.24},{"text":"But how does protecting the public at large from people who have committed a crime in the armed forces, how does that have anything to do with regulating the armed forces.","start":1447.509,"stop":1456.782,"duration":9.27}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"That is inherent in taking somebody who violated Federal law and imposing appropriate sanctions on them for that violation.","start":1456.782,"stop":1465.138,"duration":8.36}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Dreeben, it would help me in answering some of these questions if you went through the analysis on the assumption that this was instead a Commerce Clause case.","start":1465.138,"stop":1473.058,"duration":7.92},{"text":"So take the military out of it; what would the necessary and proper analysis look like?","start":1473.058,"stop":1478.029,"duration":4.97}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"It would look essentially the same, Justice Kagan.","start":1478.029,"stop":1481.314,"duration":3.29},{"text":"Somebody who violates a Federal law that's premised on the Commerce Clause, say a sex offender who travels in interstate commerce with the intent to commit a sex offense, has placed himself within the regulatory authority of the Federal Government.","start":1481.314,"stop":1497.625,"duration":16.31},{"text":"Now, that individual can be criminally prosecuted for that violation, and that violation furthers Congress's interests in regulating interstate commerce.","start":1497.625,"stop":1507.648,"duration":10.02},{"text":"Congress could also decide, you know, for some of these sex offenders, criminal punishment is not the right approach.","start":1507.648,"stop":1514.369,"duration":6.72},{"text":"The right approach is mandate sex offender rehabilitative counseling.","start":1514.369,"stop":1519.773,"duration":5.4},{"text":"And it might discover that that's so effective for a class of offenders that it's going to apply that even to people whose offenses were committed before the law in question is passed.","start":1519.773,"stop":1531.496,"duration":11.72},{"text":"It can't punish those people based on retroactive legislation, but it can reach them with a civil remedial measure so long as it passes through the Comstock-type analysis of the Necessary and Proper Clause.","start":1531.496,"stop":1546.673,"duration":15.18}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Dreeben, you say nothing about the -- what was the opening argument in -- in your brief, that the assumption that SORNA is something new added after is wrong because there were these predecessor laws that established a Federal requirement to register.","start":1546.673,"stop":1570.121,"duration":23.45}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"Justice Ginsburg, I believe that the Fifth Circuit was wrong on that too.","start":1570.121,"stop":1574.109,"duration":3.99},{"text":"As we describe in our brief, Title 42 Section 14072(i)(3) and (4) did, in our view, impose criminal punishment on Respondent for failing to register as a sex offender at the time he was in the military.","start":1574.109,"stop":1590.202,"duration":16.09},{"text":"We think the Fifth Circuit was wrong on that statutory analysis, but, more fundamentally, the Fifth Circuit was wrong in thinking that it mattered whether he was under some sort of Federal criminal jurisdiction at the time that he was released from Federal custody.","start":1590.202,"stop":1605.561,"duration":15.36},{"text":"And if I could reserve the rest of my time.","start":1605.561,"stop":1607.163,"duration":1.6}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, Mr. Dreeben.","start":1607.163,"stop":1608.213,"duration":1.05},{"text":"Ms. Fuentes.","start":1608.213,"stop":1615.519,"duration":7.31}]},{"speakerName":"M. Carolyn Fuentes","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1615.519,"stop":1616.286,"duration":0.77},{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court:","start":1616.286,"stop":1619.221,"duration":2.93},{"text":"The Government asks this Court to go beyond its holding in United States v. Comstock to allow the Federal Government to reach back, after a Federal sentence has expired, to bring back into Federal control a person who has returned to the authority of the State.","start":1619.221,"stop":1636.683,"duration":17.46},{"text":"And I'm quite surprised to hear the Government say that this is not a Comstock analysis.","start":1636.683,"stop":1643.354,"duration":6.67},{"text":"I'm not sure they stuck with that throughout the argument, but I think the Comstock factors are factors that this Court looks at quite frequently in doing any kind of a necessary and proper analysis.","start":1643.354,"stop":1654.977,"duration":11.62}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Going back to -- to a prior question, are you challenging -- you didn't on appeal, but it seems as if you're accepting that the Federal Government has the power to impose this requirement as part of a Federal sentence.","start":1654.977,"stop":1672.356,"duration":17.38}]},{"speakerName":"M. Carolyn Fuentes","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that's correct.","start":1672.356,"stop":1673.739,"duration":1.38}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":1673.739,"stop":1674.475,"duration":0.74},{"text":"Are you -- if it's not part of a Federal sentence but part of release, it's not announced at the sentence but it's announced at the time the prisoner is put into supervised release or release from jail, do you think the Government has the power to impose it then?","start":1674.475,"stop":1692.186,"duration":17.71}]},{"speakerName":"M. Carolyn Fuentes","textObjs":[{"text":"In this case, on these facts and based on the Federal statutes that exist today, the answer is yes.","start":1692.186,"stop":1699.506,"duration":7.32},{"text":"And the illustration, I think, is the way that SORNA works today.","start":1699.506,"stop":1703.994,"duration":4.49},{"text":"As the Government mentioned--","start":1703.994,"stop":1706.21,"duration":2.22}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, SORNA today becomes part of the supervised relief terms.","start":1706.21,"stop":1710.731,"duration":4.52}]},{"speakerName":"M. Carolyn Fuentes","textObjs":[{"text":"--Correct.","start":1710.731,"stop":1711.298,"duration":0.57}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm not talking about SORNA today.","start":1711.298,"stop":1713.266,"duration":1.97}]},{"speakerName":"M. Carolyn Fuentes","textObjs":[{"text":"Okay.","start":1713.266,"stop":1713.816,"duration":0.55}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm talking about just any prisoner who has been in jail but it's not made, has not been paid, part of the punishment.","start":1713.816,"stop":1723.456,"duration":9.64}]},{"speakerName":"M. Carolyn Fuentes","textObjs":[{"text":"I think the law permits a sentencing judge -- I'm not talking about Congress, but a sentencing judge -- to go back and impose additional conditions of supervised release.","start":1723.456,"stop":1736.013,"duration":12.56}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I don't know of that power, but do you have a statutory--","start":1736.013,"stop":1739.667,"duration":3.65}]},{"speakerName":"M. Carolyn Fuentes","textObjs":[{"text":"It's 18 -- 18 United States Code Section 3583.","start":1739.667,"stop":1744.302,"duration":4.63},{"text":"And 3583 permits the sentencing judge to change conditions of supervised release based on the factors that are considered important in sentencing in 18 United States Code Section 3583.","start":1744.302,"stop":1757.462,"duration":13.16}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"--All right.","start":1757.462,"stop":1757.845,"duration":0.38},{"text":"So that power -- I guess then what the Government is saying, as I understand their argument, if you have the power to do it at that point, why can't you have the power to do it later?","start":1757.845,"stop":1768.335,"duration":10.49}]},{"speakerName":"M. Carolyn Fuentes","textObjs":[{"text":"Well--","start":1768.335,"stop":1769.269,"duration":0.93}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Are the same factors that compel permission for the Government to do it then?","start":1769.269,"stop":1774.221,"duration":4.95}]},{"speakerName":"M. Carolyn Fuentes","textObjs":[{"text":"--It's because the way the statute works, even though it wasn't announced at sentence, supervised release is considered to be part of the sentence.","start":1774.221,"stop":1784.112,"duration":9.89},{"text":"So if I understand the question correctly, the reason the court can go back and impose those conditions and possibly the reason that Congress can go back and do it is because those statutes that I've mentioned, 3583 and 3553, have given notice to the individual.","start":1784.112,"stop":1801.538,"duration":17.43}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"We are not talking -- I'm sorry.","start":1801.538,"stop":1803.407,"duration":1.87}]},{"speakerName":"M. Carolyn Fuentes","textObjs":[{"text":"That's all right.","start":1803.407,"stop":1804.457,"duration":1.05}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I didn't mean to interrupt your question.","start":1804.457,"stop":1805.542,"duration":1.08}]},{"speakerName":"M. Carolyn Fuentes","textObjs":[{"text":"It's all right.","start":1805.542,"stop":1806.142,"duration":0.6}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"We're not talking about statutory authorization.","start":1806.142,"stop":1808.643,"duration":2.5},{"text":"We are talking about constitutional power.","start":1808.643,"stop":1811.429,"duration":2.79},{"text":"So if we start out with the example of registration for life being imposed as part of supervised release, part of the criminal sentence, then we go to an example where it is not part of the criminal sentence but it is a civil requirement triggered by a separate civil proceeding for every Federal -- every person convicted of a sex offense under Federal law.","start":1811.429,"stop":1838.763,"duration":27.33},{"text":"Now, if that were the setup statutorily, would that fall within Congress's power under Article I?","start":1838.763,"stop":1845.567,"duration":6.8}]},{"speakerName":"M. Carolyn Fuentes","textObjs":[{"text":"I think not, but I want to qualify that because it depends on what powers Congress is relying on.","start":1845.567,"stop":1852.006,"duration":6.44},{"text":"And let me give an example.","start":1852.006,"stop":1853.472,"duration":1.47},{"text":"I know the Government was -- a lot of the Government's argument relies on this difference between criminal and civil consequences.","start":1853.472,"stop":1860.676,"duration":7.2}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we know what -- and we know what power they are relying on.","start":1860.676,"stop":1862.862,"duration":2.19},{"text":"Let's just look at the power that they're relying on here: It's the power to make rules for the regulation of the military.","start":1862.862,"stop":1868.616,"duration":5.75},{"text":"So part of their -- in the exercise of their power to make rules for the regulation of the military, they impose a civil sex offender registration requirement for someone convicted of a sex offense under the Uniform Code of Military Justice.","start":1868.616,"stop":1884.109,"duration":15.49},{"text":"That does not, in your judgment, fall within Article I?","start":1884.109,"stop":1887.513,"duration":3.4}]},{"speakerName":"M. Carolyn Fuentes","textObjs":[{"text":"It does if the person is still in the military or if he has been -- or if he has committed a criminal offense and the prosecutorial power, the Federal power to prosecute him for that offense, has not been exhausted, yes, that can be done.","start":1887.513,"stop":1901.753,"duration":14.24}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"How about if he is on supervised release?","start":1901.753,"stop":1903.522,"duration":1.77},{"text":"He is not in the military, but his entire sentence has not been completed.","start":1903.522,"stop":1909.176,"duration":5.65}]},{"speakerName":"M. Carolyn Fuentes","textObjs":[{"text":"I think if he is still being supervised by the military, then I think it's likely that power exists.","start":1909.176,"stop":1917.449,"duration":8.27}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Okay.","start":1917.449,"stop":1918.649,"duration":1.2},{"text":"Then why not this?","start":1918.649,"stop":1919.465,"duration":0.82}]},{"speakerName":"M. Carolyn Fuentes","textObjs":[{"text":"Because Mr. Kebodeaux was not on supervised release.","start":1919.465,"stop":1924.686,"duration":5.22}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Well -- why not?","start":1924.686,"stop":1925.503,"duration":0.82},{"text":"I mean, look, this is -- Thomas Reed Powell once said,","start":1925.503,"stop":1930.173,"duration":4.67},{"text":"\"If you can think of a thing that is inextricably related to another thing without thinking of the other thing, then you have the legal mind. \"","start":1930.173,"stop":1936.91,"duration":6.74},{"text":"and that seems to be this case.","start":1936.91,"stop":1939.445,"duration":2.53},{"text":"All right?","start":1939.445,"stop":1940.028,"duration":0.58}]},{"speakerName":"M. Carolyn Fuentes","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, but--","start":1940.028,"stop":1940.647,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"So somehow I have to get out of my mind the ex post facto part, the potential violation of due process part, the equal protection part, take that aside.","start":1940.647,"stop":1950.336,"duration":9.69},{"text":"Now I've got to just think about whether it has, the Congress has the power under the provision that Justice Alito said.","start":1950.336,"stop":1957.757,"duration":7.42},{"text":"I'm trying to do that, and I've dissented in other cases on other grounds.","start":1957.757,"stop":1962.811,"duration":5.05},{"text":"All right.","start":1962.811,"stop":1963.311,"duration":0.5},{"text":"But in -- in just trying to do that, I think, well, the military, suppose they found a certain number of -- of individuals, men or women, have unfortunate problems in the military.","start":1963.311,"stop":1975.987,"duration":12.68},{"text":"They discover there is a mental illness problem; the person's out of the military.","start":1975.987,"stop":1981.891,"duration":5.9},{"text":"But the law says you can go and tell the local mental health authorities about this person even though he's no longer there.","start":1981.891,"stop":1990.128,"duration":8.24},{"text":"And suppose the person had a criminal problem in the military and was in prison and suppose the law said, you know, you're the ones who got the situation where he unfortunately got into that problem, and you, later on, can -- can go and tell authorities about his problems so they can take appropriate action.","start":1990.128,"stop":2009.209,"duration":19.08},{"text":"Now, if they can do that, why can't they have the power under Article I to say really, you all have to register.","start":2009.209,"stop":2018.647,"duration":9.44},{"text":"Now, maybe there are other things, but you got this problem in the military.","start":2018.647,"stop":2022.432,"duration":3.79},{"text":"You were convicted in the military.","start":2022.432,"stop":2023.968,"duration":1.54},{"text":"You did it in the military.","start":2023.968,"stop":2025.618,"duration":1.65},{"text":"We turned you loose and there you are, and we want, as part of our military regulation, to be able to tell authorities about you and to make you register according to State law.","start":2025.618,"stop":2037.209,"duration":11.59},{"text":"Now, no due process problem; I have to assume that away.","start":2037.209,"stop":2042.013,"duration":4.8},{"text":"No punishment, bad punishment problem, none of those.","start":2042.013,"stop":2044.798,"duration":2.79},{"text":"But it's a power, all right?","start":2044.798,"stop":2047.084,"duration":2.29},{"text":"Why not?","start":2047.084,"stop":2047.834,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"M. Carolyn Fuentes","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, the power can't go to both of the examples that you've given.","start":2047.834,"stop":2050.702,"duration":2.87},{"text":"I don't see any problem with them giving notice.","start":2050.702,"stop":2053.153,"duration":2.45},{"text":"That does not impose a Federal obligation on an individual.","start":2053.153,"stop":2056.605,"duration":3.45},{"text":"So there is no power being exerted on the individual.","start":2056.605,"stop":2059.724,"duration":3.12},{"text":"They can have a public -- a public protection purpose and they can tell -- tell authorities who need to deal with the individual, and those authorities may have the power through State power--","start":2059.724,"stop":2071.132,"duration":11.41}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Where you're leading me, because I'm not so worried about this case, but where you're leading me is down in Commerce Clause cases and all kinds of other cases, suddenly a distinction arises that Congress can, in fact, do all kinds of things having Federal authorities do this and that, but you couldn't make someone in a State -- you know, you can imagine a few that are coming into my mind -- and so what I'm worried about is following this distinction into other areas.","start":2071.132,"stop":2099.699,"duration":28.57}]},{"speakerName":"M. Carolyn Fuentes","textObjs":[{"text":"--I don't think that is a problem, and I think the reason is I disagree fundamentally with the Government.","start":2099.699,"stop":2105.003,"duration":5.3},{"text":"I think necessary and proper analysis is important in each case and it does bear similarities in each case.","start":2105.003,"stop":2111.573,"duration":6.57},{"text":"But depending on the power being relied upon, the analysis can be quite different.","start":2111.573,"stop":2117.894,"duration":6.32},{"text":"Commerce Clause is a very broad power.","start":2117.894,"stop":2120.263,"duration":2.37},{"text":"I can't say whether this sort of thing, depending on the Commerce Clause, would be right or would be wrong.","start":2120.263,"stop":2124.648,"duration":4.39},{"text":"Look at the power to make a uniform rule of naturalization.","start":2124.648,"stop":2128.016,"duration":3.37}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, let me -- let me try this chain of reasoning out on you and -- and get your reaction.","start":2128.016,"stop":2132.152,"duration":4.14},{"text":"We're starting out with the power of Congress to make rules for the regulation of the military.","start":2132.152,"stop":2137.289,"duration":5.14},{"text":"And one of the things that they want to do in making those rules is to make military installations acceptable to the local communities where they are located.","start":2137.289,"stop":2148.077,"duration":10.79},{"text":"They know from experience, for example, it's happened in Okinawa, that when have you military personnel who go -- who commit sex offenses with people off base, it can cause tremendous opposition.","start":2148.077,"stop":2160.154,"duration":12.08},{"text":"And this is what happened here; not the opposition, but an offense involving a 15-year-old girl who lived off the base.","start":2160.154,"stop":2167.325,"duration":7.17},{"text":"So in order to ensure that there -- we don't have excessive civilian opposition to the location of military bases, we are going to do a number of things.","start":2167.325,"stop":2178.533,"duration":11.21},{"text":"One thing is we're going to criminally prosecute members of the military who commit these offenses.","start":2178.533,"stop":2184.103,"duration":5.57},{"text":"This will deter; this will incapacitate.","start":2184.103,"stop":2186.804,"duration":2.7},{"text":"But also, to provide further assurance to the community that these people are not going to be dangerous, we are going to require them to register.","start":2186.804,"stop":2194.558,"duration":7.75},{"text":"Now, maybe that's too attenuated, but I'd like to get your reaction.","start":2194.558,"stop":2198.446,"duration":3.89},{"text":"Why could Congress not do that under the Necessary and Proper Clause?","start":2198.446,"stop":2201.914,"duration":3.47}]},{"speakerName":"M. Carolyn Fuentes","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think while that person is still within the criminal jurisdiction, or any Federal jurisdiction, it could be done.","start":2201.914,"stop":2210.587,"duration":8.67},{"text":"I think that once that jurisdiction has been exhausted, once the criminal prosecution power has been exhausted, once the person has returned to the authority of the State, and I think that analysis is important always.","start":2210.587,"stop":2223.662,"duration":13.07}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"You don't have to go that far though to -- to distinguish the example that Justice Alito just gave.","start":2223.662,"stop":2229.215,"duration":5.55},{"text":"This is not a statute which only requires him to registrate -- to register if he hangs around the military installation.","start":2229.215,"stop":2236.904,"duration":7.69},{"text":"This requires him to registrate anywhere, you know, in the -- in the wilds of Alaska where -- it's just not this case.","start":2236.904,"stop":2247.777,"duration":10.87},{"text":"And even -- even if you would allow that, and say it is a reasonable -- it has a reasonable connection to the power to regulate the military, to say wherever he goes he has to register is -- is a different question, isn't it?","start":2247.777,"stop":2263.389,"duration":15.61}]},{"speakerName":"M. Carolyn Fuentes","textObjs":[{"text":"I think it may well be.","start":2263.389,"stop":2263.572,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"But yet, now that's exactly the problem for me, because the -- the wilds of Alaska you think I think, and I think I think, that -- that sure, if there's a post office there -- there's a post office there, then what -- the military is all right, they can mail a letter to the -- to be delivered to the local doctor to say, look, he has a problem.","start":2263.572,"stop":2288.004,"duration":24.43},{"text":"That seems to be okay.","start":2288.004,"stop":2290.122,"duration":2.12},{"text":"But you say it's not going to be okay to tell him he has to go and make that registration.","start":2290.122,"stop":2295.174,"duration":5.05},{"text":"At that point what you've done is like Madison.","start":2295.174,"stop":2297.526,"duration":2.35},{"text":"I mean, it's an interpretation of the Commerce Clause that I think Madison might have wanted, which is you're reading a lack of power because of a civil rights problem.","start":2297.526,"stop":2306.216,"duration":8.69},{"text":"I mean, it's -- the difference between the two cases is really not the need because we have to assume the need.","start":2306.216,"stop":2314.571,"duration":8.36},{"text":"The difference is the restriction on the individual.","start":2314.571,"stop":2317.106,"duration":2.54},{"text":"And it's that part that I'm suddenly worried about the Commerce Clause and every power in Article I being read with exceptions in the civil rights area even though we have the amendments to protect the civil rights problems.","start":2317.106,"stop":2332.783,"duration":15.68}]},{"speakerName":"M. Carolyn Fuentes","textObjs":[{"text":"I haven't thought of it that way and that really isn't the argument that I'm making.","start":2332.783,"stop":2338.52,"duration":5.74},{"text":"I think that the military has jurisdiction.","start":2338.52,"stop":2340.972,"duration":2.45},{"text":"It's gotten information about this individual when it had power over him and they can talk to whomever they care to about him, or whether--","start":2340.972,"stop":2347.126,"duration":6.15}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"We've never -- we've never held, have we, that what the Federal Government can itself do under the Necessary and Proper Clause it can impose upon individuals to do under the Necessary and Proper Clause?","start":2347.126,"stop":2362.218,"duration":15.09},{"text":"Aren't there two different -- what is necessary and proper for the Federal Government itself to do is not necessarily necessary and proper for the Federal Government to require private individuals to do.","start":2362.218,"stop":2373.943,"duration":11.73}]},{"speakerName":"M. Carolyn Fuentes","textObjs":[{"text":"--I absolutely agree with that.","start":2373.943,"stop":2375.978,"duration":2.03},{"text":"And I think that this goes back to something that the Government -- well, it gives me an opportunity to address something the Government has said about the Fifth Circuit's opinion.","start":2375.978,"stop":2384.216,"duration":8.24},{"text":"That it is a per se rule, and that is just incorrect.","start":2384.216,"stop":2388.302,"duration":4.09},{"text":"I -- I have to disagree with that.","start":2388.302,"stop":2389.886,"duration":1.58},{"text":"And I have to disagree with it because the -- everything the Fifth Circuit said was limited by these facts.","start":2389.886,"stop":2396.808,"duration":6.92},{"text":"These facts are what controls the case.","start":2396.808,"stop":2399.843,"duration":3.03},{"text":"And the Fifth Circuit took great care to make a very narrow ruling.","start":2399.843,"stop":2405.164,"duration":5.32},{"text":"And that ruling, the Fifth Circuit said, is that it's unconstitutional, SORNA's requirements, as applied to Mr. Kebodeaux and others like him.","start":2405.164,"stop":2413.751,"duration":8.59},{"text":"It has no effect on Congress's ability to impose conditions on a prisoner's release from custody or on Congress's ability to effect the registration requirements for anyone who has been convicted after SORNA's enactment.","start":2413.751,"stop":2429.529,"duration":15.78},{"text":"So really, it is not a per se rule.","start":2429.529,"stop":2431.731,"duration":2.2},{"text":"It is a rule, maybe you call it per se as it -- as it affects people in Mr. Kebodeaux's position, but I think that is very different from what the Government is arguing.","start":2431.731,"stop":2440.837,"duration":9.11}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"I guess, Ms. Fuentes, what I don't quite understand about the argument, this goes back to Justice Alito's original question.","start":2440.837,"stop":2445.139,"duration":4.3},{"text":"You seem to say that if this -- if Congress passed a civil statute like this one within the time that Mr. Kebodeaux was in custody or within the time that he was under supervised release, that that would be appropriate.","start":2445.139,"stop":2463.668,"duration":18.53},{"text":"But I guess what I don't get is why the Federal interests change, whether it's the day before he gets out of supervised release or the day after he gets out of supervised release.","start":2463.668,"stop":2474.773,"duration":11.11},{"text":"What in the Federal interests shift based on that?","start":2474.773,"stop":2479.693,"duration":4.92}]},{"speakerName":"M. Carolyn Fuentes","textObjs":[{"text":"I'll answer that question first, then come back to another.","start":2479.693,"stop":2483.812,"duration":4.12},{"text":"It's not a question, I don't think, of Federal interest.","start":2483.812,"stop":2487.699,"duration":3.89},{"text":"It's a question of Federal power.","start":2487.699,"stop":2490.033,"duration":2.33},{"text":"And you have to look at the individual power being exercised.","start":2490.033,"stop":2493.27,"duration":3.24},{"text":"And so the way I look at it is what's the difference if the Federal Government makes a rule for a person in the military before -- when he's in the military or after he gets out of the military?","start":2493.27,"stop":2505.911,"duration":12.64},{"text":"That's all the difference in the world.","start":2505.911,"stop":2507.395,"duration":1.48},{"text":"In -- in -- that's our argument.","start":2507.395,"stop":2510.899,"duration":3.5},{"text":"That is all the difference in the world.","start":2510.899,"stop":2511.832,"duration":0.93}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I wasn't assuming that he was in the military while he was on supervised release.","start":2511.832,"stop":2514.683,"duration":2.85}]},{"speakerName":"M. Carolyn Fuentes","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm sorry.","start":2514.683,"stop":2516.033,"duration":1.35},{"text":"I didn't hear.","start":2516.033,"stop":2516.802,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"I was assuming that he was out of the military in both these cases, but that you said while he was still serving his sentence, it would be appropriate for Congress to add this additional thing, but not after.","start":2516.802,"stop":2528.943,"duration":12.14}]},{"speakerName":"M. Carolyn Fuentes","textObjs":[{"text":"I think--","start":2528.943,"stop":2530.576,"duration":1.63}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"In both cases, he's not in the military anymore.","start":2530.576,"stop":2532.728,"duration":2.15}]},{"speakerName":"M. Carolyn Fuentes","textObjs":[{"text":"--Constitutionally, it -- it can be all right constitutionally, depending on the statutory procedures that govern it.","start":2532.728,"stop":2542.184,"duration":9.46},{"text":"And the way that the Federal law operates now, the statutes that I mentioned, 3583 and 3553, the way those statutes -- statutes operate is they -- they give someone notice that their conditions of supervised release can be -- can be changed.","start":2542.184,"stop":2556.008,"duration":13.82},{"text":"And so there isn't an ex post facto problem with that.","start":2556.008,"stop":2559.043,"duration":3.04},{"text":"And there isn't a power problem with that, because the criminal -- the power to make the criminal offense and punish it still exists while that person is on supervised release.","start":2559.043,"stop":2570.501,"duration":11.46},{"text":"It has expired with respect to Mr. Kebodeaux, and I think that is one of the most important points in this case, and it goes along with the Comstock analysis.","start":2570.501,"stop":2581.659,"duration":11.16}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Is it your argument that Congress lacks the power to impose supervised release after the date when the person leaves the military?","start":2581.659,"stop":2589.498,"duration":7.84}]},{"speakerName":"M. Carolyn Fuentes","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":2589.498,"stop":2590.381,"duration":0.88},{"text":"After the criminal sentence is served.","start":2590.381,"stop":2593.55,"duration":3.17},{"text":"I'm sorry.","start":2593.55,"stop":2595.401,"duration":1.85},{"text":"Maybe I didn't understand the question.","start":2595.401,"stop":2597.219,"duration":1.82}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Someone is sentenced to prison--","start":2597.219,"stop":2601.02,"duration":3.8}]},{"speakerName":"M. Carolyn Fuentes","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":2601.02,"stop":2601.638,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--under the UCMJ, released, dishonorably discharged from the military.","start":2601.638,"stop":2609.209,"duration":7.57},{"text":"Can Congress say the person has to remain on supervised release for a longer period of time after he is returned to civilian status?","start":2609.209,"stop":2617.648,"duration":8.44}]},{"speakerName":"M. Carolyn Fuentes","textObjs":[{"text":"Not if -- not unless it was -- that provision was imposed as part of the sentence or while he was still within the Federal power, before the Federal criminal jurisdiction expires.","start":2617.648,"stop":2631.158,"duration":13.51}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"See, I understand -- I can understand why that might create -- that might raise all sorts of constitutional arguments about notice and so forth.","start":2631.158,"stop":2638.478,"duration":7.32},{"text":"But I don't see how that -- how that connects with the question whether Congress has the power to do it under -- under Article I--","start":2638.478,"stop":2647.334,"duration":8.86}]},{"speakerName":"M. Carolyn Fuentes","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I'm not sure--","start":2647.334,"stop":2651.636,"duration":4.3}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--under the power to regulate the military.","start":2651.636,"stop":2652.769,"duration":1.13}]},{"speakerName":"M. Carolyn Fuentes","textObjs":[{"text":"--Yes.","start":2652.769,"stop":2653.321,"duration":0.55},{"text":"I'm not sure I'm answering the question correctly, but that power doesn't last forever.","start":2653.321,"stop":2656.94,"duration":3.62},{"text":"The powers -- there are some powers in the Constitution which may last longer than others, and the example I raised before was the rule of making uniform naturalization.","start":2656.94,"stop":2669.997,"duration":13.06},{"text":"That's a broader power, I think, than the military power.","start":2669.997,"stop":2673.901,"duration":3.9},{"text":"And we see that in the cases the Government's mentioned and we've mentioned, the Toth case and the Kinsella case.","start":2673.901,"stop":2679.619,"duration":5.72}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, you could be making the argument that the power to make rules for the military applies only to people who are in the military, and that once you're out of the military that power does not permit Congress to do anything special to you.","start":2679.619,"stop":2693.946,"duration":14.33},{"text":"But you're not making that argument, I gather.","start":2693.946,"stop":2696.165,"duration":2.22}]},{"speakerName":"M. Carolyn Fuentes","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":2696.165,"stop":2696.631,"duration":0.47},{"text":"No, I'm not making that argument.","start":2696.631,"stop":2698.433,"duration":1.8},{"text":"And again, it goes to the individual facts and the power asserted and the way the power operates always makes a difference.","start":2698.433,"stop":2707.038,"duration":8.61},{"text":"The example that the Government gave with that board of inquiry and being able to bring people back in, I find that whole scenario very questionable.","start":2707.038,"stop":2715.978,"duration":8.94},{"text":"But there -- there were people who were -- were receiving military benefits, if I understood it.","start":2715.978,"stop":2721.215,"duration":5.24}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"How would you write this opinion if you wanted to protect against what Justice Breyer was concerned about, constricting the Commerce Clause, which has been since Madison more broadly defined than he did, or Justice Alito's example of ensuring that you're not closing off other things that can be done after someone leaves, that might be related to, like punishing a crime that you find out about afterwards.","start":2721.215,"stop":2754.603,"duration":33.39},{"text":"How would you write this opinion?","start":2754.603,"stop":2757.055,"duration":2.45}]},{"speakerName":"M. Carolyn Fuentes","textObjs":[{"text":"Just the way the Fifth Circuit did in its en banc opinion.","start":2757.055,"stop":2760.423,"duration":3.37}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it wasn't really helpful, because it -- it doesn't give us a limiting principle like -- I don't know if it's possible -- that if you're relying on just recidivism, Congress has to have an independent basis, a power for the imposition of -- of criminal or civil sanctions on someone.","start":2760.423,"stop":2784.372,"duration":23.95}]},{"speakerName":"M. Carolyn Fuentes","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm not certain an opinion like that could be written.","start":2784.372,"stop":2787.407,"duration":3.04},{"text":"I think that the limits, the limitations that exist, are on the narrowness of the way the opinion is written.","start":2787.407,"stop":2793.911,"duration":6.5},{"text":"But future cases I don't think can be decided that way.","start":2793.911,"stop":2797.346,"duration":3.43},{"text":"Certainly, principles can be articulated which help to limit.","start":2797.346,"stop":2801.167,"duration":3.82},{"text":"And I think the -- the best you can say in terms of limiting principles is it's going to depend on the enumerated power upon which the government relies to impose this obligation.","start":2801.167,"stop":2813.975,"duration":12.81}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, how -- I'm not sure that makes much sense.","start":2813.975,"stop":2816.36,"duration":2.39},{"text":"You're saying if they're relying on the enumerated power with respect to the military, they can do more than if they're relying on the enumerated power over interstate commerce?","start":2816.36,"stop":2824.782,"duration":8.42}]},{"speakerName":"M. Carolyn Fuentes","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":2824.782,"stop":2825.499,"duration":0.72},{"text":"And if that's your understanding--","start":2825.499,"stop":2826.649,"duration":1.15}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"So in what sense--","start":2826.649,"stop":2827.567,"duration":0.92}]},{"speakerName":"M. Carolyn Fuentes","textObjs":[{"text":"--I -- I apologize.","start":2827.567,"stop":2828.667,"duration":1.1},{"text":"I did not mean that.","start":2828.667,"stop":2829.451,"duration":0.78}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, in what sense does it then depend on which enumerated power they're invoking?","start":2829.451,"stop":2834.555,"duration":5.1}]},{"speakerName":"M. Carolyn Fuentes","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, let -- let me give an example that goes to the collateral consequence cases that the Government raised.","start":2834.555,"stop":2840.142,"duration":5.59},{"text":"The Government raises, for example, the Hudson case, where a person who is convicted of bank fraud both can be punished criminally and then can be debarred civilly from participating any more with Federal Government contracts.","start":2840.142,"stop":2853.85,"duration":13.71},{"text":"I think the words that were used in the Hudson case were","start":2853.85,"stop":2857.254,"duration":3.4},{"text":"\"no longer may have business doings with an insured bank. \"","start":2857.254,"stop":2862.824,"duration":5.57},{"text":"Okay, that has to be, I think, the spending power.","start":2862.824,"stop":2866.276,"duration":3.45},{"text":"The Government can decide with whom it wants to do business.","start":2866.276,"stop":2868.811,"duration":2.54},{"text":"If it's dealing with an insured bank, then it can impose that civil consequence.","start":2868.811,"stop":2873.68,"duration":4.87},{"text":"And it can do it -- I don't want to use the word “ independently ” of.","start":2873.68,"stop":2877.215,"duration":3.54},{"text":"They may do it by reason of the criminal conviction, but there is an independent power to do it.","start":2877.215,"stop":2882.452,"duration":5.24},{"text":"That power doesn't exist here, and so it would have to be--","start":2882.452,"stop":2886.606,"duration":4.15}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"They say -- they say it exists by virtue of the enumerated power to regulate the military forces.","start":2886.606,"stop":2891.575,"duration":4.97}]},{"speakerName":"M. Carolyn Fuentes","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, I don't think it does.","start":2891.575,"stop":2894.594,"duration":3.02},{"text":"Perhaps I don't understand the--","start":2894.594,"stop":2895.879,"duration":1.28}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I'm trying to see why you're saying the enumerated power under the Spending Clause allows them to take this subsequent action, but the enumerated power under the Military Clause does not.","start":2895.879,"stop":2905.817,"duration":9.94}]},{"speakerName":"M. Carolyn Fuentes","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, because the -- I'm sorry.","start":2905.817,"stop":2907.269,"duration":1.45}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I would have thought that if you're arguing under the Necessary and Proper Clause, that you need an enumerated power that the Necessary and Proper Clause is going to serve.","start":2907.269,"stop":2917.125,"duration":9.86},{"text":"But I don't see how it makes a difference which enumerated power you're talking about.","start":2917.125,"stop":2921.011,"duration":3.89}]},{"speakerName":"M. Carolyn Fuentes","textObjs":[{"text":"I think it all -- I think it does turn on the nature of the power.","start":2921.011,"stop":2925.065,"duration":4.05},{"text":"I mean, could you use the military power to say you, Mr. Bank Fraud Client, cannot contract with the Government any more?","start":2925.065,"stop":2933.754,"duration":8.69},{"text":"No.","start":2933.754,"stop":2934.354,"duration":0.6}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I get to ask the questions.","start":2934.354,"stop":2935.471,"duration":1.12},{"text":"You don't.","start":2935.471,"stop":2935.971,"duration":0.5},{"text":"[Laughter]","start":2935.971,"stop":2937.289,"duration":1.32}]},{"speakerName":"M. Carolyn Fuentes","textObjs":[{"text":"Sorry.","start":2937.289,"stop":2938.756,"duration":1.47},{"text":"You are so correct on that.","start":2938.756,"stop":2939.908,"duration":1.15},{"text":"I apologize.","start":2939.908,"stop":2940.741,"duration":0.83}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"No, but it's the military -- look, it's the military that they are mostly -- that they're relying on.","start":2940.741,"stop":2946.061,"duration":5.32}]},{"speakerName":"M. Carolyn Fuentes","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2946.061,"stop":2946.894,"duration":0.83},{"text":"And it--","start":2946.894,"stop":2947.644,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"So they say -- I mean, the famous statement -- I looked it up --","start":2947.644,"stop":2949.613,"duration":1.97},{"text":"\"Let the end be legitimate, let it be within the scope of the Constitution, and all means which are appropriate and not forbidden are -- fall within the Necessary and Proper Clause. \"","start":2949.613,"stop":2959.636,"duration":10.02},{"text":"All right?","start":2959.636,"stop":2960.052,"duration":0.42},{"text":"The end is to protect the communities from those individuals in respect to those matters that they became dangerous with when they were in the military; okay?","start":2960.052,"stop":2971.51,"duration":11.46},{"text":"That's the end.","start":2971.51,"stop":2972.462,"duration":0.95},{"text":"And is the means appropriate?","start":2972.462,"stop":2975.331,"duration":2.87},{"text":"They say yes.","start":2975.331,"stop":2976.281,"duration":0.95},{"text":"They say, after all, the means here is, notify them when we're -- you're moving around.","start":2976.281,"stop":2981.235,"duration":4.95},{"text":"And therefore, is it forbidden?","start":2981.235,"stop":2984.437,"duration":3.2},{"text":"Well, we're not supposed to consider that part, but -- so leave that out.","start":2984.437,"stop":2987.971,"duration":3.53},{"text":"But the -- the others, they say is okay.","start":2987.971,"stop":2991.19,"duration":3.22},{"text":"So that's the basic.","start":2991.19,"stop":2991.723,"duration":0.53},{"text":"Do you think maybe we should send this back to the -- to the Fifth Circuit?","start":2991.723,"stop":2994.892,"duration":3.17},{"text":"The Government suggests that--","start":2994.892,"stop":2995.911,"duration":1.02}]},{"speakerName":"M. Carolyn Fuentes","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well--","start":2995.911,"stop":2996.761,"duration":0.85}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"--because they didn't get it right in respect to what the previous statutes require.","start":2996.761,"stop":3000.529,"duration":3.77},{"text":"What about all that?","start":3000.529,"stop":3001.279,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"M. Carolyn Fuentes","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, the Fifth Circuit did get it right with respect to the previous statute.","start":3001.279,"stop":3004.783,"duration":3.5},{"text":"And the reason that the Government wants to send it back is because they say that the Fifth Circuit relied on the fact that Mr. Kebodeaux was unconditionally released.","start":3004.783,"stop":3014.789,"duration":10.01},{"text":"And as a matter of fact, he was unconditionally released.","start":3014.789,"stop":3018.075,"duration":3.29},{"text":"But they equate unconditional release with release free from a registration requirement.","start":3018.075,"stop":3023.479,"duration":5.4},{"text":"We have gone over that in great length in our brief.","start":3023.479,"stop":3027.346,"duration":3.87},{"text":"The Government is simply wrong about that, for the reasons that we state in our brief.","start":3027.346,"stop":3031.25,"duration":3.9},{"text":"And I can go into those, if you want, if you'd like.","start":3031.25,"stop":3033.517,"duration":2.27}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"I just want to know what to do if I end up thinking they are right.","start":3033.517,"stop":3037.571,"duration":4.05}]},{"speakerName":"M. Carolyn Fuentes","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3037.571,"stop":3038.104,"duration":0.53},{"text":"They are--","start":3038.104,"stop":3038.804,"duration":0.7}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"What's your recommendation there on that assumption?","start":3038.804,"stop":3045.242,"duration":6.44},{"text":"I'm not saying I would, but I'm just saying on that assumption.","start":3045.242,"stop":3047.61,"duration":2.37}]},{"speakerName":"M. Carolyn Fuentes","textObjs":[{"text":"--I -- I guess it depends on which assumption.","start":3047.61,"stop":3049.796,"duration":2.19},{"text":"The Fifth Circuit would not have changed its opinion in this case because Mr. Kebodeaux, as a matter of fact, whether the Government agrees or not, was not released on condition that he comply with sex offender registration requirements.","start":3049.796,"stop":3063.722,"duration":13.93},{"text":"You can see the difference between Mr. Kebodeaux's release and the release of a person who is released on conditions that he comply with requirements, and that is in 35--","start":3063.722,"stop":3076.196,"duration":12.47}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Your argument is he was released on condition of State registration.","start":3076.196,"stop":3079.481,"duration":3.29},{"text":"Isn't your argument dependent only on that there was no Federal registration requirement?","start":3079.481,"stop":3085.385,"duration":5.9}]},{"speakerName":"M. Carolyn Fuentes","textObjs":[{"text":"--No.","start":3085.385,"stop":3085.985,"duration":0.6},{"text":"It is dependent on whether that release was conditioned on his registration, and it wasn't.","start":3085.985,"stop":3093.408,"duration":7.42},{"text":"Today, when a person is released from custody on supervised release, it is a condition of that release under 3583 that he comply with sex offender registration requirements.","start":3093.408,"stop":3105.299,"duration":11.89},{"text":"What happens if he doesn't comply?","start":3105.299,"stop":3107.666,"duration":2.37},{"text":"He can go back to prison on the original conviction, because he was released on condition that he comply with Federal sex offender requirements.","start":3107.666,"stop":3117.706,"duration":10.04},{"text":"It just goes to -- to the judge.","start":3117.706,"stop":3119.892,"duration":2.19},{"text":"It's by preponderance of the evidence.","start":3119.892,"stop":3121.625,"duration":1.73},{"text":"That is not what happened here.","start":3121.625,"stop":3123.277,"duration":1.65},{"text":"Mr. Kebodeaux was released, not on any conditions.","start":3123.277,"stop":3127.546,"duration":4.27},{"text":"Now, the State may have imposed an independent obligation to register, but that was not a condition of his release.","start":3127.546,"stop":3134.568,"duration":7.02},{"text":"And so it is not the case, as a matter of fact, that he was released on condition.","start":3134.568,"stop":3140.389,"duration":5.82}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"The bottom line is you don't think the Wetterling Act applied to him.","start":3140.389,"stop":3142.489,"duration":2.1},{"text":"Is that your point?","start":3142.489,"stop":3143.341,"duration":0.85}]},{"speakerName":"M. Carolyn Fuentes","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm sorry?","start":3143.341,"stop":3143.858,"duration":0.52}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"The Wetterling Act didn't apply to him; is that--","start":3143.858,"stop":3145.808,"duration":1.95}]},{"speakerName":"M. Carolyn Fuentes","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":3145.808,"stop":3146.21,"duration":0.4},{"text":"I don't think the Wetterling Act applied to him.","start":3146.21,"stop":3147.893,"duration":1.68}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"--At all?","start":3147.893,"stop":3148.16,"duration":0.27}]},{"speakerName":"M. Carolyn Fuentes","textObjs":[{"text":"Correct.","start":3148.16,"stop":3149.244,"duration":1.08},{"text":"But even if it did, it was -- it's far removed from a registration requirement.","start":3149.244,"stop":3154.879,"duration":5.63},{"text":"It is a penalty, not a registration requirement.","start":3154.879,"stop":3158.45,"duration":3.57},{"text":"The State imposed a registration requirement.","start":3158.45,"stop":3161.052,"duration":2.6},{"text":"Wetterling did not.","start":3161.052,"stop":3162.902,"duration":1.85},{"text":"And if you'd just read -- and I think that's what the Fifth Circuit did.","start":3162.902,"stop":3165.504,"duration":2.6},{"text":"They just read the statute, 14072(i)(3) and (i)(4).","start":3165.504,"stop":3171.325,"duration":5.82},{"text":"It doesn't say a person who is required to register will follow -- will suffer the following punishment.","start":3171.325,"stop":3177.312,"duration":5.99},{"text":"It says a person described in 4042(d), a person who's been into a court-martial.","start":3177.312,"stop":3182.966,"duration":5.65},{"text":"If you look at the rest of 14072 and parts of 14071, there are provisions that say such and such person shall register.","start":3182.966,"stop":3193.671,"duration":10.7},{"text":"That is a registration requirement.","start":3193.671,"stop":3195.206,"duration":1.54}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I guess what I'm not understanding, Ms. Fuentes, is -- I understand the difference between a requirement of registration and a penalty for failing to register, but it's a little bit cutting -- slicing the baloney thin.","start":3195.206,"stop":3207.331,"duration":12.13},{"text":"And if you think that he was in any event while he was undergoing his sentence subject to a penalty, it's a pretty minor exercise of Federal power, isn't it, to say that, instead of making you just subject to a penalty for doing something, we're going to tell you, you have to do it?","start":3207.331,"stop":3227.059,"duration":19.73}]},{"speakerName":"M. Carolyn Fuentes","textObjs":[{"text":"I guess I don't.","start":3227.059,"stop":3229.378,"duration":2.32},{"text":"And the reason is it's not the degree of power exerted, it's whether the power exists.","start":3229.378,"stop":3236.183,"duration":6.8},{"text":"And once Mr. Kebodeaux completed his Federal sentence, the military power, which permitted him to be prosecuted and punished, had expired.","start":3236.183,"stop":3245.722,"duration":9.54},{"text":"And so in some ways it's like there's Federal enclave jurisdiction on this side of the street where the base exists, where the Navy yard exists, and things that happened here can be punished by the Federal Government, but just across the street the exact same things can occur and the Federal Government cannot punish it.","start":3245.722,"stop":3264.268,"duration":18.55},{"text":"So I think it is very careful to draw those fine lines, and I think it is essential when discussing issues of the enumerated powers, because they are limited.","start":3264.268,"stop":3273.439,"duration":9.17},{"text":"I don't mean to move on fast.","start":3273.439,"stop":3275.975,"duration":2.54},{"text":"I did want to mention -- I know my time is almost up -- that we have offered an alternative ground for deciding the constitutional questions here: The effective date argument.","start":3275.975,"stop":3286.866,"duration":10.89},{"text":"I know we didn't raise it in the Fifth Circuit, but this Court has the authority to consider it, and we have put into our brief all the reasons that Mr. Kebodeaux is not covered by SORNA to begin with.","start":3286.866,"stop":3295.889,"duration":9.02},{"text":"In the Sixth, Ninth and Third Circuits, he could not be prosecuted under SORNA, and so that is an alternative basis that I think the Court can decide this case on.","start":3295.889,"stop":3304.995,"duration":9.11},{"text":"And if there are no other questions, I will cede the rest of my time.","start":3304.995,"stop":3309.88,"duration":4.89}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, counsel.","start":3309.88,"stop":3312.215,"duration":2.34},{"text":"Mr. Dreeben, you have three minutes remaining.","start":3312.215,"stop":3314.433,"duration":2.22}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, Mr. Chief Justice.","start":3314.433,"stop":3316.402,"duration":1.97},{"text":"As I understand Respondent's argument, Respondent concedes that he could have been put under a lifetime requirement to register with State authorities and punished federally if he did not, if only that requirement had been imposed on him either at the time of sentencing or in a parallel civil proceeding that occurred while he was in the military.","start":3316.402,"stop":3339.049,"duration":22.65},{"text":"This case, therefore, reduces to a question of timing.","start":3339.049,"stop":3343.036,"duration":3.99},{"text":"The essential argument that Respondent is making is that Congress had its -- had its authority expire because it didn't exercise it.","start":3343.036,"stop":3351.475,"duration":8.44},{"text":"There's some sort of notion that Congress must speak now or forever hold its peace.","start":3351.475,"stop":3357.212,"duration":5.74}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"But that's not unusual.","start":3357.212,"stop":3358.129,"duration":0.92},{"text":"When you're released from the military, for example, you're no longer subject to -- to Congress's jurisdiction over the military.","start":3358.129,"stop":3364.949,"duration":6.82},{"text":"That's a matter of timing too, isn't it?","start":3364.949,"stop":3366.651,"duration":1.7}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's just wrong, Justice Scalia, because this Court made clear in United States ex rel Toth v. Quarles that if an individual has left the military but hasn't been prosecuted, they can't be court-martialed, but they can be prosecuted in an Article III clause.","start":3366.651,"stop":3382.245,"duration":15.59}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Not for something that they've done after they left the military.","start":3382.245,"stop":3385.363,"duration":3.12},{"text":"That's a question of timing.","start":3385.363,"stop":3386.53,"duration":1.17},{"text":"Had they left the military when they committed this crime?","start":3386.53,"stop":3389.115,"duration":2.58},{"text":"If so, they can't be prosecuted under -- under that power of the Federal Government.","start":3389.115,"stop":3393.885,"duration":4.77}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"But sex offender registration is a consequence of the military crime.","start":3393.885,"stop":3398.17,"duration":4.28},{"text":"That was committed while they were in the military.","start":3398.17,"stop":3400.889,"duration":2.72},{"text":"It's a civil remedy that may, consistent with other constitutional provisions, be imposed retroactively.","start":3400.889,"stop":3407.478,"duration":6.59},{"text":"And this case comes down not to whether any member of the Court agrees with the Ex Post Facto Doctrine analysis in Smith v. Doe or whether there might be due process or other concerns out there, it comes down to whether Congress has Article I authority to say--","start":3407.478,"stop":3422.905,"duration":15.43}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And that's not limited.","start":3422.905,"stop":3424.072,"duration":1.17},{"text":"You've limited it to sex offenses, but the -- Congress could say it's important to us that people who serve in the military behave correctly even after they're released.","start":3424.072,"stop":3434.295,"duration":10.22},{"text":"So it is a Federal offense to do anything that violates State law for the rest of their lives, and your argument would say, well, that's part of their authority to regulate the military and so it's okay.","start":3434.295,"stop":3445.235,"duration":10.94}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"--Let me make two points about that, Mr. Chief Justice.","start":3445.235,"stop":3447.453,"duration":2.22},{"text":"First of all, a standard condition of Federal supervised release is that the individual shall not violate any Federal, State or local law, and for many sex offenders, supervised release runs for life.","start":3447.453,"stop":3459.661,"duration":12.21}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"That's part of his sentence.","start":3459.661,"stop":3461.28,"duration":1.62},{"text":"That's part of the punishment imposed.","start":3461.28,"stop":3463.482,"duration":2.2},{"text":"You assert that this is not part of the punishment imposed.","start":3463.482,"stop":3467.101,"duration":3.62}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't see any relevance that has to Article I authority; it has relevance to other constitutional provisions.","start":3467.101,"stop":3472.755,"duration":5.65},{"text":"So, insofar as supervised release does contemplate this longstanding, continuous jurisdiction, that's a feature of Federal law that the Court ought to keep in mind in the way that it writes this opinion.","start":3472.755,"stop":3483.526,"duration":10.77},{"text":"But second, if Congress passed such a law, it's not that it has carte blanche to do that, it's just that there's no per se rule that says it can't.","start":3483.526,"stop":3492.816,"duration":9.29},{"text":"The Court would--","start":3492.816,"stop":3493.518,"duration":0.7}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"So your answer to my question is yes, Congress can do that.","start":3493.518,"stop":3496.37,"duration":2.85},{"text":"It can say anyone in the military is subject for the rest of their life to Federal jurisdiction.","start":3496.37,"stop":3502.107,"duration":5.74},{"text":"Whatever is a State law crime is a Federal crime.","start":3502.107,"stop":3504.424,"duration":2.32}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"--Mr. Chief Justice, I'm not going to say no to that question, because I don't want to foreclose options that Congress may decide it's appropriate to pass, but the Court--","start":3504.424,"stop":3515.181,"duration":10.76}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":3515.181,"stop":3515.831,"duration":0.65},{"text":"Who knows what they'll do, right?","start":3515.831,"stop":3517.216,"duration":1.38}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"--But the Court does not have to agree that that is constitutional -- may I complete my sentence?","start":3517.216,"stop":3521.485,"duration":4.27}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Sure.","start":3521.485,"stop":3522.085,"duration":0.6}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"--in order to uphold this narrowly focused, tailored law that looks at a specific crime and imposes a specific requirement that's directly tied to the nature of that crime.","start":3522.085,"stop":3532.876,"duration":10.79}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, counsel, counsel.","start":3532.876,"stop":3534.578,"duration":1.7},{"text":"The case is submitted.","start":3534.578,"stop":3535.545,"duration":0.97}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Roberts Court","arguedOn":"Apr 17, 2013","petitioner":"United States","respondent":"Anthony James Kebodeaux","docket":"12-418","citation":"570 US _ (2013)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/570/12-418","lowerCourt":"United States Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit","grantedOn":"Jan 11, 2013","decidedOn":"Jun 24, 2013"}